Answer: The issue is not with the split function but with the string you are trying to split. The string "[Lcom.hexgen.ro.request.CreateRequisitionRO;" does not contain a "." character. Therefore, the split function is not splitting the string.

In your case, you can use the lastIndexOf method to find the last occurrence of ";" and then use substring to get the part of the string you want.

Here is the corrected code:

```java
public class TestStringSplit {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String testStr = "[Lcom.hexgen.ro.request.CreateRequisitionRO;";
        int lastSemicolonIndex = testStr.lastIndexOf(";");
        String lastPart = testStr.substring(lastSemicolonIndex + 1);
        System.out.println("Last part: " + lastPart);
    }
}
```

This will output:

```
Last part: CreateRequisitionRO
```

Explanation: The lastIndexOf method returns the index of the last occurrence of ";" in the string. The substring method is used to get the part of the string from the index of the last ";" to the end of the string.

Note: This code assumes that the string always ends with a ";". If there could be other characters at the end of the string, you would need to trim the string before getting the last part.

```java
public class TestStringSplit {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String testStr = "[Lcom.hexgen.ro.request.CreateRequisitionRO;";
        testStr = testStr.trim();
        int lastSemicolonIndex = testStr.lastIndexOf(";");
        String lastPart = testStr.substring(lastSemicolonIndex + 1);
        System.out.println("Last part: " + lastPart);
    }
}
```

This will output:

```
Last part: CreateRequisitionRO
```

Explanation: The trim method is used to remove any leading or trailing whitespace from the string. This is necessary because the substring method would still return the ";" character if it was at the end of the string.

